<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1338,2010]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis box="[151,330,1339,1363]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Female winged.</emphasis>
Body brown (
<figureCitation box="[489,570,1338,1362]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[541,570,1338,1362]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
); femora brown; tibiae brown with pale apex; tarsi pale; antennal segments I– II and IV–IX brown, III pale (
<figureCitation box="[487,570,1374,1398]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[539,570,1374,1398]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
); fore wing brown with a pale band near the base (
<figureCitation box="[1137,1222,1374,1398]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[1190,1222,1374,1398]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1338,2010]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Head wider than long, with no long setae; ocellar region with three pairs of setae, pair III arising on anterior margin of ocellar triangle (
<figureCitation box="[457,541,1446,1470]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[511,541,1446,1470]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
); interantennal projection with widely separated arms. Antennae 
<number box="[1286,1299,1446,1470]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="9.0">9</number>
-segmented, segment III long with an elongate pedicel and two constrictions, one at the union between the pedicel and segment, the other near the base of segment; segment IV entire and shorter than III (
<figureCitation box="[985,1115,1518,1542]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Figs 
<number box="[1042,1115,1518,1542]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="15.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="15.0">15–16</number>
</figureCitation>
), both with two rows of sensorial pores. Pronotum reticulate-striate with no long setae (
<figureCitation box="[817,900,1554,1578]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[869,900,1554,1578]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
); mesonotum reticulate-striate; metanotum with concentric sculpture around basal midpoint, covered with microtrichia (
<figureCitation box="[958,1042,1590,1614]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[1011,1042,1590,1614]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
). Fore wing with two rows of conspicuous brown setae (
<figureCitation box="[406,490,1626,1650]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[458,490,1626,1650]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1338,2010]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Abdominal tergites I–VII with sparse microtrichia on lateral thirds and posterior margin with craspedal lobes laterally, each rectangular lobe bearing a fringe of fine, irregular microtrichia (
<figureCitation box="[1029,1159,1698,1722]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Figs 
<number box="[1086,1159,1698,1722]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="17.19">17, 19</number>
</figureCitation>
). Tergites II–V posterior margin with few microtrichia medially, VI–VII with a complete feinge of microtrichial medially, with no gap between this and the lobes. Tergite VIII with continuous posteromarginal microtrichia. Sternites II–VI posterior margins with well-developed craspedal lobes bearing microtrichia (
<figureCitation box="[923,1006,1806,1830]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1949,1972]" captionTargetBox="[210,1363,195,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[210,1365,195,1929]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. pedicellatus sp. n. female 11 – 20: 11. Dorsal view; 12. Mesonotum and metanotum; 13. Head; 14. Pronotum; 15. Antennal segments II – IV; 16. A ntenna; 17. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 18. Abdominal sternites IV – VI; 19. Abdominal tergites I – III; 20. Fore wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280413/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[978,1006,1806,1830]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
) and with 
<number box="[1134,1148,1807,1830]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="7.0">7</number>
pairs of posteromarginal setae; few discal setae present.
</paragraph>
